d. Enables brute-force enumeration of registration tokens, DoS of the DB, and redirect scraping. AGENTS.md §8 acknowledges this is required before public release. | [backend/web/routes/auth.go](backend/web/routes/auth.go), [backend/web/routes/urls.go](backend/web/routes/urls.go), [backend/web/routes/redirect.go](backend/web/routes/redirect.go) | — | Add Gin middleware for per-IP rate limiting (e.g., `golang.org/x/time/rate` or `github.com/ulule/limiter`). Apply stricter limits to unauthenticated endpoints. |\n| 4 | **High** | **Session JWT and pre-registration JWT share the same signing secret** — Both `CreateJWT` and `CreatePreRegToken` use `JWT_SECRET`. `ParseJWT` accepts any token signed with that secret; a pre-reg token submitted as a Bearer header yields `JWTClaims{UserID: 0}`, which passes middleware and enters all protected handlers with a zero user ID. | [backend/web/routes/jwt.go](backend/web/routes/jwt.go#L59-L92) | 59–92, 96–120 | Use distinct secrets per token type, or embed a mandatory `typ` claim in both token types and validate it explicitly in each parse function before accepting the claims. |\n| 5 | **High** | **JWT exposed in URL fragment (`#token=…`)** — Even on legitimate same-origin redirects, the raw JWT appears in browser history, is accessible via `window.location.hash` by any first- or third-party script, and may leak through browser extensions. | [backend/web/routes/auth.go](backend/web/routes/auth.go#L137-L141) | 137–141 | Exchange the token via a short-lived one-time code instead: backend redirects to `redirectTo?code=<opaque_code>`, the frontend immediately POSTs the code to a token-exchange endpoint to receive the JWT over a JSON body, and the code is invalidated. |\n| 6 | **Medium** | **In-memory JWT blacklist is lost on server restart** — Logged-out tokens remain valid for up to 24 h after any restart, allowing session resumption post-logout. | [backend/web/routes/blacklist.go](backend/web/routes/blacklist.go) | 1–80 | Persist the blacklist in the database (or Redis if added) so it survives restarts. A simple `jwt_blacklist(jti TEXT, expires_at TIMESTAMPTZ)` table with a periodic purge is sufficient. |\n| 7 | **Medium** | **No HTTP security response headers** — Neither Gin nor the Caddyfile set `Content-Security-Policy`, `X-Frame-Options`, `X-Content-Type-Options`, `Referrer-Policy`, or `Permissions-Policy`. Absence of CSP significantly raises XSS impact; absence of `X-Frame-Options` allows clickjacking. | [deploy/Caddyfile](deploy/Caddyfile) | — | Add a `header` block in the Caddyfile (or a Gin middleware) that sends at minimum: `X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff`, `X-Frame-Options: DENY`, `Referrer-Policy: strict-origin-when-cross-origin`, and a strict CSP. |\n| 8 | **Medium** | **DNS-based SSRF bypass in URL validator** — `ValidateLongUrl` only rejects hostnames that parse as a private literal IP. A hostname such as `internal.attacker.com` resolving to `192.168.x.x` passes validation; at redirect time the user's browser is sent to the private address. This enables targeted attacks against company networks of authenticated users. | [backend/business-logic/url_validator.go](backend/business-logic/url_validator.go#L36-L47) | 36–47 | Resolve the hostname with `net.LookupHost` (non-cached, with a timeout) and apply the same private-IP check to all resolved addresses before accepting the URL. |\n| 9 | **Medium** | **`gin.Default()` in production logs all request/response metadata** — `gin.Logger()` (included by `gin.Default()`) writes every path, query string, and status code to stdout. OAuth callback query params (error codes, provider names) are captured; if logging infrastructure is compromised these expose auth-flow metadata. `gin.Recovery()` may emit partial request data on panic. | [backend/main.go](backend/main.go#L62) | 62 | Replace `gin.Default()` with `gin.New()` and attach only `gin.Recovery()`. Implement a `slog`-based request logger that explicitly selects which fields to log and masks any sensitive query params. |\n| 10 | **Low** | **Shortcode base62 generation has modulo bias** — `int(b) % 62` with a uniformly random byte (0–255) is not uniform: `256 mod 62 = 8`, so characters at positions 0–7 in the charset appear with probability 5/256 ≈ 1.95 % vs 4/256 ≈ 1.56 % for the remaining 54 characters. Over large volumes this slightly reduces the effective entropy of generated shortcodes. | [backend/business-logic/shortcode.go](backend/business-logic/shortcode.go#L47-L52) | 47–52 | Use rejection sampling: discard bytes ≥ 248 (`4 × 62`) and redraw, or switch to `math/big`-based uniform sampling. |\n\n---\n\n## Priority Summary\n\n| Priority | IDs | Action |\n|----------|-----|--------|\n| Fix immediately | #1 | Single-line server-side guard: validate `redirect_to` starts with `APP_BASE_URL` before storing in session. Closes both the open redirect and the JWT exfiltration vector. |\n| Fix before any wider exposure | #4 | Add a `typ` claim to both JWT types and validate it in each parser. Low effort, high impact. |\n| Fix before production | #2, #3, #5, #6, #7 | Token storage strategy, rate limiting, secure-header policy, blacklist persistence. |\n| Improve when time allows | #8, #9, #10 | DNS-resolve SSRF check, structured request logging, rejection-sampling in shortcode generator. |\n"},"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01BFqXMJrcKVCRnD4SYPG9nB__vscode-1773898184487","cwd":"/home/alexl70/src/pet/linkshortener"}

