{"timestamp":"2026-03-19T11:28:40.008Z","hook_event_name":"PreToolUse","session_id":"8295e5bc-ce49-481d-bff7-41354d8aae44","transcript_path":"/home/alexl70/.vscode-server/data/User/workspaceStorage/01bd222c9e9d12cff8e6ef2465541c97/GitHub.copilot-chat/transcripts/8295e5bc-ce49-481d-bff7-41354d8aae44.jsonl","tool_name":"memory","tool_input":{"command":"create","path":"/memories/session/plan.md","file_text":"# Plan: Fix Issue #1 — Open Redirect + JWT Exfiltration\n\n## TL;DR\n\nThe `/auth/login/:provider` handler validates `redirect_to` for scheme and host but does not constrain the origin. An attacker can supply an arbitrary domain, causing the JWT to be redirected to that domain after OAuth completes. The fix adds a server-side origin guard: in production mode, `redirect_to` must start with `APP_BASE_URL` (which equals the frontend origin in production since both are served from the same domain via Caddy).\n\n**Why not just use `APP_BASE_URL` in both dev and prod?** In dev, the frontend runs on port 5173 while the backend runs on port 8080, so the origins differ. In production, Caddy serves both from the same domain, making `APP_BASE_URL` the correct allowed prefix for `redirect_to`. This dev/prod split mirrors the existing CORS middleware pattern in `cors.go`.\n\n---\n\n## Steps\n\n### Phase 1 — Backend auth.go guard (1 file change)\n\n1. In `backend/web/routes/auth.go`, in the `GET /auth/login/:provider` handler, add `\"strings\"` to imports and insert a guard immediately after the existing URL format check (lines 68–71):\n   - If `LINKSHORTENER_ENV != \"dev\"` **and** `redirectTo` does not start with `os.Getenv(\"APP_BASE_URL\")`: return HTTP 400 with `{\"error\": \"redirect_to URL not allowed\"}`.\n   - In dev mode the guard is skipped (matching CORS middleware behavior).\n\n### Phase 2 — Tests (1 file change, *depends on Phase 1*)\n\n2. In `backend/web/routes/auth_test.go`, add a new test `TestLogin_ForeignOriginRedirectTo_Returns400InProdMode`:\n   - Set `t.Setenv(\"LINKSHORTENER_ENV\", \"prod\")` and `t.Setenv(\"APP_BASE_URL\", \"http://localhost:8080\")`.\n   - Issue `GET /auth/login/google?redirect_to=http%3A%2F%2Flocalhost%3A5173%2Fauth%2Fcallback`.\n   - Assert HTTP 400 response with `{\"error\": \"redirect_to URL not allowed\"}`.\n3. Verify the existing `TestLogin_ValidRedirectTo_StartsOAuthFlow` still passes (it uses `LINKSHORTENER_ENV=dev` set in `TestMain`, so the prod guard is not triggered).\n\n---\n\n## Relevant files\n\n- `backend/web/routes/auth.go` — add `\"strings\"` import and prod-mode origin guard in the `redirect_to` validation block (around line 68–71)\n- `backend/web/routes/auth_test.go` — add new regression test covering prod-mode rejection\n\n---\n\n## Verification\n\n1. Run `go test ./backend/web/routes/...` — all existing tests must pass; the new test must pass.\n2. Run `go vet ./...` — no new warnings.\n3. Manual (optional): set `LINKSHORTENER_ENV=prod` and `APP_BASE_URL=http://localhost:8080` and curl `GET /auth/login/google?redirect_to=https://evil.com/steal` — must get HTTP 400.\n\n---\n\n## Decisions\n\n- **Dev/prod split** — the guard only applies in prod mode, mirroring `CORSMiddleware` in `cors.go`. In dev, `redirect_to` may come from any localhost port for DX convenience.\n- **No new env var** — `APP_BASE_URL` already covers the production frontend URL (same domain via Caddy proxy). Adding `FRONTEND_BASE_URL` is out of scope for this targeted fix.\n- **Scope** — only back-end validation is changed; no frontend changes needed; no other security issues addressed in this fix.\n\n---\n\n## Further Considerations\n\n1. **Security report says `APP_BASE_URL` but backend and frontend URLs differ in dev.** The recommendation from the report is correct for production. The dev-mode carve-out is deliberate and consistent with existing CORS policy. Nothing to change, just noting the nuance.\n"},"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_018tKJTMJJHH5FWLMFwvFB4n__vscode-1773898184508","cwd":"/home/alexl70/src/pet/linkshortener"}

